{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17619011","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17619011"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:27:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:27:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16521"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16521","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16521"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9212"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65866"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9212","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9212"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16521"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51311"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10305"},{"type":"tags","id":"10319"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21845"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21853"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65866","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65866"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following sensory nerve fibres is primarily responsible for mediating the muscle stretch reflex?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ia","Ib","II","III","IV"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe stretch reflex (myotatic reflex) is mediated primarily by \u003Cstrong\u003EIa\u003C/strong\u003E sensory fibres, which are large, myelinated axons that innervate muscle spindles. These fibres are extremely sensitive to changes in muscle length and the velocity of stretch, making them crucial for proprioception and motor control.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIb\u003C/strong\u003E fibres innervate Golgi tendon organs and respond to changes in muscle tension rather than muscle stretch. They are important for force detection but do not mediate the stretch reflex.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EII\u003C/strong\u003E fibres are secondary muscle spindle afferents that respond to sustained stretch but are less sensitive to the dynamic changes that trigger the stretch reflex.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIII\u003C/strong\u003E fibres (mechanoreceptive) and \u003Cstrong\u003EIV\u003C/strong\u003E fibres (nociceptive) are smaller diameter fibres that carry information about touch, pressure, and pain. They are not involved in the stretch reflex pathway.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe stretch reflex is a monosynaptic reflex where Ia afferents synapse directly onto alpha motor neurons in the spinal cord. When the muscle is stretched (as when the patellar tendon is tapped), the Ia fibres increase their firing rate, causing reflex contraction of the same muscle through activation of these motor neurons. This reflex helps maintain muscle length and posture.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Group Ia sensory fibres from muscle spindles detect changes in muscle length and velocity of stretch.","Muscle spindles contain specialized intrafusal muscle fibres that are arranged in parallel with extrafusal (force-generating) muscle fibres.","The stretch reflex is a monosynaptic reflex that helps maintain muscle length and tone."],"references":["Suslak TJ, Jarman AP. Stretching the imagination beyond muscle spindles - stretch-sensitive mechanisms in arthropods. J Anat. 2015 Aug;227(2):237-42. doi: 10.1111/joa.12329. Epub 2015 Jun 16. PMID: 26076887; PMCID: PMC4523326.","Hall, J. E., \u0026 Hall, M. E. (2020). Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology E-Book: Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022).\u00a0The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Kr\u00f6ger S, Watkins B. Muscle spindle function in healthy and diseased muscle. Skelet Muscle. 2021 Jan 7;11(1):3. doi: 10.1186/s13395-020-00258-x. PMID: 33407830; PMCID: PMC7788844."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51311"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16521"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51311","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51311"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-27T11:57:43+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-27T11:58:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9212"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65866"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"descri